words: I'd gone to day-camps a lot when I was growing up in elementary school, things like that,
um, you know, horse riding-camp, just daycare, other random camps. But, I think my
biggest, um... I guess my introduction to real summer camp
was through this Disney channel show called, Bug Juice, um, and they followed
people who were staying in like an over-night camp for two weeks, and I told my mom, you know, I want to...
do an over-night camp if I can. She let me research some and I found one near Lake Tahoe
called Mountain Camp two. Um, and I signed... or... I
signed up and I went and I think, um,
you know, I still remember going there for the first time and everyone knew everyone cause they had their friends from home
and they were camp friends and I was this new girl. And, I guess I'd never really been in a
situation where I was the new person, um, you know. Up until then, I'd gone to
elementary school and middle school with the same people. Um, I had my group
of friends, you know, I knew who I wanted to hang out with and in, um,
yeah, at summer camp I had to make new friends and part of
making new friends is figuring out who you are, I think... um... or... I guess,
figuring out who you want to be. So, um,
since that summer camp, you know, I've put myself in
more and more situations where I am the new girl. I went to a... a longer camp when I was in high
school That was that Swedish language learning camp and um, you know, I was the new girl there, and,
I've moved to Australia, I was the new girl there, you know, um,
starting new jobs and the new person there, and, I think, constantly being
the new person has helped me figure out how to connect best with people. You know, I'm pretty
comfortable kind of just inserting myself into new situations now because I've done it often enough
that I know, um, A, it's not scary and, B, I know kind of different
